LINUX LOGGING OVERVIEW

SECTION 1: FUNDAMENTAL CONCEPT OF LOGGING

Logging is the continuous recording of events occurring within a system, application, or network. These events may include user actions, system processes, errors, authentication attempts, and network activity.

Logs are critical because they provide:
	•	VISIBILITY → what happened on the system
	•	TRACEABILITY → who did what and when
	•	ACCOUNTABILITY → linking actions to users
	•	EVIDENCE → used in investigations and legal cases

In cybersecurity and forensics, logs are treated as primary evidence sources. If logs are missing, incomplete, or tampered with, investigations become significantly harder or impossible.

Key properties of good logs:
	•	Accuracy (correct timestamps)
	•	Completeness (all relevant events captured)
	•	Integrity (not altered)
	•	Availability (accessible when needed)

